songs.title: You're Gonna Miss Me
songs.commentary: Saw him live at Maxwell's in 2010 and think it's interesting to pair his documentary with Daniel Johnston's. That would be a heck of a double feature.

songs.title: Do the Du (The Graveyard)
songs.commentary: This one is a hidden gem that I think many would like if they heard it. It's like a badass take on the Knight Rider theme.

songs.title: I Was Born to Sing Sad Song
songs.commentary: This group from Austin, TX - since disbanded, always felt like the female version of the music I wrote as Rare Books.

songs.title: It Never Rains in Southern California
songs.commentary: A song about California written by the dad of one of the guitarists in The Strokes.

songs.title: Lost and Found
songs.commentary: I heard Andy was having trouble sleeping when he wrote this album. I can feel it in the music. I would listen taking late night walks for cigarettes back when I smoked, blasting it in my headphones and walking down through the three graveyards that surrounded my block.

songs.title: Hatch the Plan
songs.commentary: Atmospheric and refined. Good for late night walks.

songs.title: Grass
songs.commentary: Really dreamy wild abstract song. My favorite by Animal Collective.

songs.title: Fistful of Love
songs.commentary: This is a brutal song. Stand by your man but on steroids.

songs.title: Hope There's Someone
songs.commentary: This song inspired me to buy a Boss Loop Station just so I could cover it.

songs.title: Another World
songs.commentary: Love this one, off of an EP

songs.title: Bird Guhl
songs.commentary: The conclusion of a transformation. I thank God, I am free at last.

songs.title: Xen
songs.commentary: One of the strangest songs I've ever heard

songs.title: Soon-To-Be Innocent Fun / Let's See
songs.commentary: Discovered this through a blog that mentioned it as an inspiration for James Blake and boy they weren't kidding!

songs.title: Nadie Sabe
songs.commentary: You're at a real disadvantage if you're not a Spanish speaker when it comes to really understanding this song. It's so cool to hear Benito see in 2023 that he was nowhere near his peak.

songs.title: Race In
songs.commentary: I listen to this when I want to hype myself up before working out or an important meeting. It feels like the instruments are speaking to each other and assembling like the Megazord in Power Rangers.

songs.title: Atlas
songs.commentary: This came out of left field when released and wasn't like anything I had heard before.

songs.title: Heroes and Villains
songs.commentary: Smiley Smile - whatever unfinished unofficial version that I had - was my favorite Beach Boys album. And this song in particular was my favorite among those on the album.

songs.title: Disney Girls
songs.commentary: Something so nostalgic and AM radio about this one in particular.

songs.title: Myth
songs.commentary: Having first discovered Beach House when they debuted with Devotion and kind of falling off a bit after 3 albums, it was cool to hear how epic they could sound now.

songs.title: Intergalactic
songs.commentary: I was a kid when this came out and I loved it.

songs.title: Sabotage
songs.commentary: A classic that's hard to separate from the iconic music video.

songs.title: Sexx Laws
songs.commentary: 97 Beck is so good and this is his best album pound for pound, I think

songs.title: Everybody's Gotta Learn Sometime
songs.commentary: Beck can also do sad songs. This was on Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind, a lightbulb-moment movie from my younger days

songs.title: Lost Cause
songs.commentary: Sea Change is such a departure from the irreverence of Beck's '97 release, but he can do somber well, too.

songs.title: Debra
songs.commentary: I think it's very funny that in this song the narrator is trying to pick up a girl in his Hyundai, but also he wants to get with her sister and he's really not sure, he just thinks her name is Debra. He could be wrong.

songs.title: 1000BPM
songs.commentary: Samples Herbie Hancock's Chameleon

songs.title: Little Lou, Ugly Jack, Prophet John
songs.commentary: This was the other Jack-themed song I covered during a concert for my friend Jack - who recovered from a major health emergency. It was very different than the other Jack song by The Frogs.

songs.title: The Fox in the Snow
songs.commentary: This one is beautiful and delicate, and pairs well with Françoise Hardy. Did this subconsciously influence me into writing a song called "In The Snow"? Yeah maybe.

songs.title: Sha Sha
songs.commentary: I got really into this as a teen and then got to celebrate the album's anniversary with my buddy Darren in NYC. It was fun.

songs.title: Boyfriend
songs.commentary: Simple songs but so pleasant and well done.

songs.title: Summer Mood
songs.commentary: I love this whole record. It feels like high school.

songs.title: Anti Love Song
songs.commentary: This song is so confident and sexy that it makes me uncomfortable. Good for you Betty Davis.

songs.title: Am I Black Enough for You?
songs.commentary: Kind of bad ass for Billy Paul to tackle this.

songs.title: Me and Mrs. Jones
songs.commentary: I love hearing him sing this one.

songs.title: Bachelorette
songs.commentary: What a music video this is. Good song but freaking brilliant music video, check it out!

songs.title: Hunter
songs.commentary: So ahead of its time and well produced.

songs.title: Ancestress
songs.commentary: A tribute to her late mother who passed in 2018. This video is a ceremonial burial. It's beautiful.

songs.title: Boomerang
songs.commentary: I remember learning about The Black Lips before I saw them live. They were banned from certain states for their wild shows. They would throw firecrackers out toward the audience.

songs.title: John L
songs.commentary: It's like a dystopian sci-fi novel made into an orchestral prog rock - what a story!

songs.title: Forever Heavy
songs.commentary: This is an awesome gem I fell in love with and I have no idea why this band isn't more popular than they are.

songs.title: Don't Run Our Hearts Around
songs.commentary: I saw them live at Maxwell's and had to leave the concert early for some reason or another. Not a good enough reason, highly regret it.

songs.title: Modern Music
songs.commentary: What an opener to their debut record. 1 - 2 - 3 another pop explosion!

songs.title: Colors
songs.commentary: Black Pumas were a fun discovery and I got to see them live before COVID hit at Asbury Park.

songs.title: Shuffle Your Feet
songs.commentary: Country-ish rock music had a moment for me in the early 2000s

songs.title: Ain't No Easy Way
songs.commentary: This was one of two BRMC songs I dig - but haven't explored much of their full discography since

songs.title: Paranoid
songs.commentary: RIP Ozzy. This song makes me want to be a drummer.

songs.title: Elephant Woman
songs.commentary: You have to be okay with the vocals to like Blonde Redhead, but if you can be okay with that - what a treat.

songs.title: The Dress
songs.commentary: 23 was a great album by Blonde Redhead, maybe their best. And this song from it is great.

songs.title: Who Do You Love?
songs.commentary: Billy Atwell turned me on to Bo Diddley. His lyrics are fantastic. What a badass.

songs.title: The Man in Me
songs.commentary: Reminds me of The Big Lebowski, one of my favorite comedies. T-bone Burnett assembled the soundtrack and he did a great job. I also saw Bob in Hoboken. The locals were not expecting modern Bob.

songs.title: You're Gonna Make Me Lonesome When You Go
songs.commentary: Love the lyrics: But I'll see you in the sky above in the tall grass in the ones I love. I was moping about a breakup one summer, sitting along the hudson and listening to this album on repeat.

songs.title: Beyond Here Lies Nothin'
songs.commentary: Kind of reminds me of late stage Tom Waits. Or like the theme from The Wire.

songs.title: For Emma, Forever Ago
songs.commentary: Bon Iver is kind of lame and I don't like his new stuff but I can't deny this. This is good.

songs.title: Blood Bank
songs.commentary: An EP cut from Bon Iver shortly after his big album. Makes me think of the winter and being on a bus ride home while listening to it.

songs.title: I'd Rather Be With You
songs.commentary: Love Bootsy and this tune and how often its been sampled and interpolated. It's no accident bay buh!

songs.title: Backwaters
songs.commentary: Who doesn't love hearing about the heuristics of the mystics. Lots of fun wordplay in the lyrics here with a focus on the sound of the words mostly.

songs.title: Some of Them Are Old
songs.commentary: Not many Brian Eno songs where the lyrics are the thing that moves me, but this one does.

songs.title: Untrue
songs.commentary: This is the sort of dubstep I like. Charles at Tunes, the record shop I worked at, put me on this.

songs.title: Frank Sinatra
songs.commentary: I enjoy the random 'yahs' in the background of many Cake songs and the liberal use of the vibraslap.

songs.title: Comfort Eagle
songs.commentary: Feels like a sneak peak behind the curtain of the music biz

songs.title: Hey Lloyd, I'm Ready to be Heartbroken
songs.commentary: Fun fact: this was written as a response to "Are You Ready to Be Heartbroken" by Lloyd Cole. Love it when songs reference other songs.

songs.title: Vitamin C
songs.commentary: Maybe the most well-known CAN song. It's a banger.

songs.title: I'm So Green
songs.commentary: CAN - so far ahead of their time and Ege Bamyasi is always a solid pick.

songs.title: Her Eyes Are A Blue Million Miles
La pluie du ciel
songs.commentary: A real gem I discovered through a music blog that covered international music.

songs.title: Construção
songs.commentary: Key words in the verses of this song swap with each variation, changing the meaning of the song. A man goes to work on a construction site for the last time. I recommend reading the English translation for this one.

songs.title: Cálice
songs.commentary: So much to discuss here but Cálice in Portugese when spoken sounds both like the word "Chalice" like the vessel and "Shut Up" like censorship. The song is written as if it's a critique of the Catholic church but it was actually a critique of the government. Artists had to find clever ways to slip things past actual government agencies that would review content. I can't believe how possible this seems in 2026.

songs.title: Touch Red
songs.commentary: So cinematic, this one.

songs.title: SS Cygni
songs.commentary: Dan, an experimental musician I befriended, exposed me to Chrome. I immediately loved it. It reminded me of a lot of the Krautrock I liked but more aggressive.

songs.title: Fancy Footwork
songs.commentary: Chromeo was lots of fun in a way that not much music is anymore.

songs.title: Werewolf
songs.commentary: I kind of picture Phil and Lil from the Rugrats rapping this one

songs.title: By Your Side
songs.commentary: French sisters making avant garde music with toys

songs.title: Noah's Ark
songs.commentary: There's a number of songs from CocoRosie in here and I like them

songs.title: Animals
songs.commentary: CocoRosie is an acquired taste you'll either love or hate.

songs.title: Fear of the Unknown and the Blazing Sun
I-Feel-Like-I'm-Fixin'-to-Die Rag
songs.commentary: Vietnam bad. War bad. Kazoos good.

songs.title: Crimewave
songs.commentary: So cool. Alice Glass embodies all that quiet cool of like the best baristas whose lives I've imagined.

songs.title: Untrust Us
songs.commentary: Glitchy dirty dance music - real shame about how terrible that dude was to Alice though.

songs.title: Let's Make Love and Listen to Death From Above
songs.commentary: I love this song but don't know the first thing about Death From Above 1979. I like this song better than their more popular single "Music is My Boyfriend"

songs.title: Really Love
songs.commentary: I saw this live on SNL and it blew my mind. D'Angelo was so talented

songs.title: How Does It Feel
songs.commentary: I was too young when this came out to appreciate it, but it's a classic. Neo-soul. History won't forget D'Angelo.

songs.title: Cookies with a Smile
songs.commentary: A silly song from an electronic group who like to perform while sustaining solely on bananas and champagne. Gotta respect the gimmick.

songs.title: Story of an Artist
songs.commentary: Sad song that can make me cry, especially after watching a documentary on the guy.

songs.title: Don't Let the Sun Go Down on Your Grievances
songs.commentary: I like the way he pronounces grievances

songs.title: Funeral Home
songs.commentary: Simple effective lyrics on this one.

songs.title: Really Doe
songs.commentary: Danny Brown's voice is enjoyably annoying

songs.title: Ain't It Funny
songs.commentary: This reminds me of like - The Joker from the original Batman TV show. Maybe he's sampling that I dunno, it's zany in the best way.

songs.title: Five Years
songs.commentary: I listened to this way too much during the first few months of the pandemic.

songs.title: Oh! You Pretty Things
songs.commentary: How did Bowie come up with those melodies?!

songs.title: The Dream Before The Ring That Woke Me
songs.commentary: I got this as a promo CD at the record store, was curious because of the album art and really liked this song and how it builds up.

songs.title: My Body's a Zombie for You
songs.commentary: You know Ryan Gosling? Not only is he a handsome actor, but he's also a pretty good musician. I bust this one out during Halloween, this is him singing.

songs.title: Hacker
songs.commentary: Complex and written in a way that almost seems like its in code. Gaga can't handle this shit.

songs.title: Guillotine
songs.commentary: My favorite Death Grips song. Serial number! Killing machine!

songs.title: Digital Bath
songs.commentary: Teenage Efrain was horrified when he learned about the story behind this song.

songs.title: My Own Summer (Shove It)
songs.commentary: Maybe my favorite song by The Deftones, I think.

songs.title: Trashcan
songs.commentary: Met one of the guitarists of the band playing a live show at Pete's Candy Store two days after Christmas. We talked about The Big Lebowski. I was surprised he had a day job.

songs.title: Enjoy the Silence
songs.commentary: Words are very... unnecessary

songs.title: So Long Old Bean
songs.commentary: Who is old bean, or rather - what is old bean? No idea. Love this song.

songs.title: The Body Breaks
songs.commentary: A simple and beautiful tune by a key part of that freak folk revival I was so into in the early 2000s.

songs.title: How Deep is the Ocean
songs.commentary: I was recommended this guy by a lawyer who would shop at the record store. There was a compilation of his stuff and this song in particular stood out. I like pairing it with The Ocean by Richard Hawley.

songs.title: We Are Rockstars
songs.commentary: Feels somewhere between Justice and The Go! Team. If you're feeling like something between that with a bit of The Rapture mixed in, this'll do it.

songs.title: Season of the Witch
songs.commentary: Donovan seems like he was probably more real than Dylan.

songs.title: Oh No
songs.commentary: I like how many parts this song has

songs.title: California
songs.commentary: Philly's own - singing about the west coast.

songs.title: Say Something
songs.commentary: I met Dr. Dog's manager - he was the sound guy at Maxwell's and helped my loop pedal sound good. Goes to show - don't be rude to sound guys. He later got them booked to tour with Wilco and let me handle merch at The Bowery Ballroom for a free ticket and I think I got some merch out of it. Nice guy, can't recall his name.

songs.title: Wake Up
songs.commentary: I got to work the merch table for Dr. Dog at the Bowery Ballroom right before they were set to begin touring with Wilco.

songs.title: Mr. Snuggles
songs.commentary: This outsider music tune has no business being this good. This is a very very catchy melody. Thanks to Irwin Chusid and his Songs in the Key of Z for bringing this to my attention. He's a DJ on WFMU still and he's great.
Kool Keith is so weird and awesome, this is the lead track off his Dr. Octagon album. Carvel don't tell – your whole crew's ice cream, fudge!

songs.title: Blue Flowers
songs.commentary: Saw this live during All Tomorrow's Parties in Asbury Park... it was really bad. Kool Keith didn't seem to know the words.

songs.title: Ta Det Lugnt
songs.commentary: I couldn't understand how people could enjoy music in a language they didn't speak until I started listening to Dungen. No idea what they're saying but boy do I want to keep hearing it.

songs.title: Fumbling Over Words That Rhyme
songs.commentary: I think Edan also sampled Harry Nilsson's The Point, which was narrated by Ringo Starr. Solid sample here, too.

songs.title: Bombay
songs.commentary: If Animal Collective was Colombian. This dude also produced a lot of cool music from artists including Rosalía.

songs.title: Freight Train
songs.commentary: What a beautiful song. I think I found out about this from WFMU.

songs.title: Between the Bars
songs.commentary: I was just getting into Elliott Smith when he passed and it was really upsetting. Then I bought a book about his life that at the time was good but looking back, seemed maybe too soon to release after his death.

songs.title: Happiness
songs.commentary: Melancholy like much of Elliott's songs. I would play this a lot on train rides to and from my high school girlfriend's town when I was a senior.

songs.title: Say Yes
songs.commentary: So sweet, this one. Not unlike "Hope There's Someone" by Antony and the Johnsons - this one has a vocalist exist as one voice and then become two mid-song. I believe "Oh Comely" by Neutral Milk Hotel does the same thing.

songs.title: Gymnopédie No. 1
songs.commentary:
Slanting and shadow-cutting a bursting torrent
Streamed in floods of gold upon the polished flagstone
Where the atoms of flaming amber gleaming
Mingled their sarabande with the gymnopædia.

songs.title: The Healer
songs.commentary: I enjoy New Amerykah pt 1 and this one is maybe the most accessible? It's good.

songs.title: The F*****g Moon
songs.commentary: I think this song is actually sampling an old audio bit by The Onion. Either way, it does make me laugh.

songs.title: It's Alright Ma, It's Only Witchcraft
songs.commentary: It was illegal to make bad music in 1968, it seems.

songs.title: The Sad Skinhead
songs.commentary: Satirical, and musically interesting. Nothing like the rest of the album. Pairs really well with Bitter's End by Roxy Music

songs.title: Shakara (Ologe)
songs.commentary: This was the first Fela song I heard. It got me used to longer form songs which opened me up to his other work.

songs.title: Coffin for Head of State
songs.commentary: Fela wrote this after the government raided his home and put his mother through a window.

songs.title: When I Grow Up
songs.commentary: Side project of The Knife that's witchy and cool - great art direction for the whole project

songs.title: Sleep to Dream
songs.commentary: In the words of Fiona... this world? This world is bullshit.

songs.title: Sun It Rises
songs.commentary: I've heard Fleet Foxes were boring live, but I really enjoyed their records and harmonies.

songs.title: Dancing on the Ceiling
songs.commentary: The first concept album was by Frank Sinatra. If I have to listen to him, I'll pick this first album - thanks.

songs.title: In the Wee Small Hours of the Morning
songs.commentary: Early Sinatra is the only Sinatra I can handle. Great music backing this, too.

songs.title: Take Me Out
songs.commentary: Love the two part structure and got to meet these dudes and see them live at a meet and greet at Virgin Records when it was open in Times Square.

songs.title: Comment te dire adieu
songs.commentary: Beautiful French women singing beautiful songs - melting

songs.title: Le temps de l'amour
songs.commentary: I knew about this song before the Wes Anderson placement, but I don't mind it being used. It's a great song

songs.title: Tous les garçons et les filles
songs.commentary: Fun Fact: French 'Ye ye ye' music was called as such because of the influence The Beatles had with songs like "She Loves You"

songs.title: Can You Get to That
songs.commentary: Maggot Brain is great and I like to play this song after Rill Rill by Sleigh Bells if I have control of the proverbial aux cable since it samples it

songs.title: Damaged Goods
songs.commentary: The wordplay here with change and the till and damaged goods, it's all very clever. Refund the cost, indeed.

songs.title: 6.4 = Make Out
songs.commentary: One of the strangest songs. I'd love to see Gary Wilson live someday.

songs.title: Gary's in the Park
songs.commentary: Catchy outsider music. Gary sings a lot about the park.

songs.title: Behind That Locked Door
songs.commentary: Simple chords, simple words but really deep feeling. When I hear songs like this it's hard not to say George is my favorite Beatle.

songs.title: Run to Your Mama
songs.commentary: On my bucket list to see live, for sure.

songs.title: The Dead Flag Blues
songs.commentary: Cinematic and epic, this one.

songs.title: Chalice Hymnal
songs.commentary: Kind of brings to mind the music of Razor Ramon, a childhood pro-wrestling hero. He was Cuban, like me - but in reality he was played by a white guy maybe more convincingly than Al Pacino?

songs.title: Go (feat. Blood Diamonds)
songs.commentary: Grimes wrote this one so that Rihanna would record it. She passed. It's a good one and I'm glad she put it out because I think Rihanna would have cut some of the more wild parts.

songs.title: Oblivion
songs.commentary: The OG Grimes song where I was absolutely crushin' on her. So cool seeing her pull this off live and I appreciated that she was self-producing stuff.

songs.title: Tractor Rape Chain
songs.commentary: I listened to a lot of GBV but so far only this song has stuck.

songs.title: Thy Will Be Done
songs.commentary: If Beck could just be cooler, it would sound like this, I think.

songs.title: Without You
songs.commentary: Did you know this song isn't originally by Mariah? I thought for a while Harry Nilsson wrote it but he didn't either. It was Badfinger.

songs.title: Everybody's Talkin'
songs.commentary: Love this song even though I've never been able to sit through Midnight Cowboy.

songs.title: Many Rivers to Cross
songs.commentary: Harry was losing his voice the Summer John Lennon agreed to record this album with him. He pushed through because he didn't want to stop recording with him. I think this was during the wild summer where Harry and John were kicked out of the Smothers Brothers and were just a real "sick team" together causing chaos.

songs.title: Mucho Mungo / Mt. Elga
songs.commentary: What a keyboard sound on this, shimmering. Feels like vacation.

songs.title: No More Hotdogs
songs.commentary: It's strange, but then it gets stuck in your head. Then you're in trouble.

songs.title: Chameleon
songs.commentary: This was the gateway that got me into Headhunters. It's such a good album.

songs.title: Blind
songs.commentary: Anohni singing on this one, my favorite on the album, with some of my favorite artwork.

songs.title: Drop Off
songs.commentary: Higgins is a band my friend Brian and Kevin formed and they also were my backing band for my self-released EP. This is my favorite song by them and it was recorded in their apartment in Weehawken, NJ. They were Tame Impala before Tame Impala.

songs.title: Nightclubbing
songs.commentary: I believe this was produced by Bowie? This is peak Iggy Pop, in my opinion.

songs.title: Sister Midnight
songs.commentary: Was this in Trainspotting? Or was that Nightclubbing? Not sure but I like this song.

songs.title: The First Girl I Loved
songs.commentary: Heartfelt and honest, you can just feel it.

songs.title: Either Way
songs.commentary: Jang Wonyoung is a divisive figure in the K-pop community. This song is really delicate and vulnerable in a way that IVE isn't typically.

songs.title: KOD
songs.commentary: I don't know a ton about J. Cole but I do like this song.

songs.title: The Wilhelm Scream
songs.commentary: The first James Blake song I heard. I'm seeing him live soon and I can't wait.

songs.title: Don't Let Him Waste Your Time
songs.commentary: One of the funniest music videos you'll see - a zany sort of take on Karma Police maybe? I think this samples "Crimson and Clover" - it felt retro and classic even when it first came out.

songs.title: My Shadow
songs.commentary: This is my favorite JR song pound-for-pound

songs.title: My Family
songs.commentary: RIP Jay Reatard

songs.title: Death Is Forming
songs.commentary: So loud and powerful, this one. Manic. Anxious. Intense.

songs.title: The Red
songs.commentary: Chris at the record shop would play a lot of MF Doom and Madlib - I'm glad he did and this collab between Madlib and J Dilla always stood out to me.

songs.title: The Chelsea Hotel Oral Sex Song
songs.commentary: A kind of hilarious Anti-Folk song. I got to meet this guy at an open mic in the west village and smoke a cigarette while learning his middle name is "Lightning," legitimately. He showed me his ID.

songs.title: like JENNIE
songs.commentary: Blackpink's own. Really cool production that didn't play it safe.

songs.title: Fast Forward
songs.commentary: I'm secretly a K-pop fan and this is one of a few I'll share. I think it could stand toe to toe with some western pop hits, easily.

songs.title: Extra
songs.commentary: Jeon Somi's father is a Marine I believe, and she studied Taekwondo. So beyond the fitness from dance - there's a power to her that I think is a result of the martial arts background.

songs.title: Peach Plum Pear
songs.commentary: I have read the right books to interpret your looks - what a lyric! Fun fact, she's married to Andy Samberg.

songs.title: Remember
songs.commentary: John wrote this while he was going through six months of primal therapy where he would relive childhood trauma. As someone whose childhood wasn't all rosy - this album really resonated with me.

songs.title: God
songs.commentary: I was listening to this deeply in my Dostoyevsky phase in college.

songs.title: Yeah Right
songs.commentary: Formerly a YouTuber named Filthy Frank who was like a worse Eric Andre, what a flip to this tender song-maker.

songs.title: She's Lost Control
songs.commentary: Really sad story - Joy Division. Look it up.

songs.title: Isolation
songs.commentary: Moody and sparse, lovely!

songs.title: We Travel the Spaceways
songs.commentary: There's something delicate about how June sings this one. It makes me smile every time. I don't think I ever listen to it just once if it comes up.

songs.title: Genesis
songs.commentary: I got a pre-release copy of this record from an A&R person when I worked at the record shop. They were obsessed with it - and I became obsessed with it, too.

songs.title: D.A.N.C.E.
songs.commentary: This is a sick song with a fun performance on Jimmy Kimmel which used a variety of iconic impersonators.

songs.title: Something on Your Mind
songs.commentary: Lovely lyrics and a voice that grew on me, then again I like Neutral Milk Hotel so...

songs.title: DNA
songs.commentary: Confidence distilled into a rap song

songs.title: Pro Nails
songs.commentary: I heard about Kid Sister through her association with Spank Rock and this one stuck with me.

songs.title: In The Court of the Crimson King
Baby Blue
songs.commentary: Something so relaxed and casual about this one's beauty. It feels effortless.

songs.title: Got the Life
songs.commentary: Teenage Efrain was into Korn and had their merch

songs.title: Blind
songs.commentary: Teenage Efrain got burned CDs with old Korn songs from the older 16 year old kids on the block, haha

songs.title: Can't Get You Out of My Head
songs.commentary: Undeniably catchy candy pop song. There is a cover by The Flaming Lips but the OG is better. Na Na Na - it's not that deep.

songs.title: Losing My Edge
songs.commentary: This speaks to me deeply as an ex-record store employee, and was a a list of artists to explore through

songs.title: Antifragile
songs.commentary: K-pop by way of Reggaeton beats with a growth mindset message and bad ass choreography with an apocalyptic music video theme? Seems to check a lot of boxes.

songs.title: Friendship Station
songs.commentary: I wanna be there. I wanna take you there.

songs.title: The Empty
songs.commentary: I went to your concert and I didn't feel anything.

songs.title: Curly Locks
songs.commentary: I don't know much about dub, to be honest. Chris at the record store was a big fan of Lee "Scratch" Perry and I liked this one a lot.

songs.title: Bird on the Wire
songs.commentary: Classic songwriting. I have tried in my way to be free.

songs.title: Suzanne
songs.commentary: My favorite song by Leonard Cohen, it's simple and well written and beautiful.

songs.title: Lovesick
songs.commentary: A strange one that's still accessible.

songs.title: Rumble
songs.commentary: This song was banned from the radio. It was the only song without lyrics to be banned from the radio.

songs.title: Ain't That Loving You Baby
songs.commentary: Link Wray created distortion by poking a hole in his amp. Pioneer - dude. This isn't "Rumble" which is the one by him everyone knows, I like this one a lot and he sings on it.

songs.title: Andy's Chest
songs.commentary: Written about the attempted assassination of Andy Warhol who supported The Velvet Underground.

songs.title: El Touchy
songs.commentary: I have the full record with other Touchy songs on it. Don't forget the very strict rules about a Touchy and what makes it a Touchy. If it doesn't meet that criteria then - well my friend it's sad to say it but it just isn't a touchy.

songs.title: Born Free
songs.commentary: This samples "Ghost Rider" by Suicide and it GOES HARD

songs.title: Revolver
songs.commentary: This EP was like a throwback to Lee Hazelwood and Ann Margret. What polar opposites, vocally. I love the line 'at 12 o clock a bell starts ringing, a dog starts barking, and you're still missing.'

songs.title: Prime
songs.commentary: Great gym music - Prime. If I don't listen to Battles to hype me up, this will do.

songs.title: Transformer
songs.commentary: A total shame more people don't know about Marnie Stern, this album was one of my favorites that year.

songs.title: Fade Into You
songs.commentary: I have such a crush on Hope Sandoval. Apparently she had real stage fright. Her performance here is gorgeous. To be able to feel so intimate in such a large venue is impressive. I always hear this song when I'm taking off on planes.

songs.title: Numb
songs.commentary: The charming vocals and production are great and this bass line is sick.

songs.title: Someone's Missing
songs.commentary: It's a shame this record wasn't popular, I like it better than the debut in some aspects.

songs.title: Don't Stop Till You Get Enough
songs.commentary: Undeniable in its status as a legendary pop song

songs.title: Don't Take Your Love From Me
songs.commentary: I don't know how I find these old tunes but when one sticks, I hang on to it. This was one that when I discovered it, I played it like non-stop for a week.

songs.title: Black Satin
songs.commentary: I love how loose and messy On The Corner is, and like other albums it inspired like Embryonic by The Flaming Lips

songs.title: We Can't Stop
songs.commentary: I think this song captures something deeper than it seems? You never feel like it'll stop when you're that age, you can't even imagine it, but it kind of does and you can stop.

songs.title: Um Gosto de Sol
songs.commentary: A dreamy multi-part song that kind of makes me think about A Day in the Life

songs.title: Voices of Spring
songs.commentary: Moondog was a blind dude who dressed like a Viking

songs.title: Some Trust All
songs.commentary: Moondog wrote songs in rounds, very cool

songs.title: Dondante
songs.commentary: A slow burner that's excellent live. Love the lyrics and build up and the way it winds down with the sax.

songs.title: Anytime
songs.commentary: My first taste of My Morning Jacket was this poppy hit in 2006

songs.title: Golden
songs.commentary: In my 20s I thought this would for sure be my wedding song. Love is more complex than this, though.

songs.title: Southern Man
songs.commentary: The outro goes so hard.

songs.title: Harvest Moon
songs.commentary: A pretty one that makes me want to be outside.

songs.title: Hallogallo
songs.commentary: Maybe the quintessential Krautrock song?

songs.title: Oh Comely
songs.commentary: This feels like the climax of In The Aeroplane Over the Sea. Jeff Mangum mentioned the inspiration from Anne Frank and near the end we get lyrics — "I know they buried her body with others, her sister and mother and five hundred families. And will she remember me fifty years later? I wished I could save her in some sort of time machine."

songs.title: The King of Carrot Flowers Pt. 1
songs.commentary: This one has vivid pictures of a dysfunctional family and two people who fall in love among it. It reminds me of the way memory worked in my childhood home. Some walls with great and awful memories like these layers projected over them. The line "This is the room one afternoon I knew I could love you and from above you how I sank into your soul..." is one of my favorite NMH lyrics.

songs.title: Gardenhead / Leave Me Alone
songs.commentary: The part about the angels filling up the garden with snow and then rhyming in angles... it's all very beautiful and well done. I know the voice is an acquired taste.

songs.title: Engine (1993)
songs.commentary: My favorite Neutral Milk Hotel b-side. I had this on vinyl for a while - a full box set of the entire discography. I had to sell it in 2015 for essentials like food and bills. I hope I come across it again.

songs.title: Ditto
songs.commentary: I do like some K-pop and this one is pretty dang catchy. This group got in a whole legal mess though and it doesn't look like they'll be back with all members if they're even able to get through it.

songs.title: One of These Things First
songs.commentary: I can't say I have a deep reflection on Nick Drake or anything, but I do like this song.

songs.title: The Fairest of the Seasons
songs.commentary: Haunting song by Nico

songs.title: These Days
songs.commentary: I knew about this before the Wes Anderson films, but I don't mind them being used in those films, either.

songs.title: I've Got It Bad and That Ain't Good
songs.commentary: A sweet song that I later discovered plays during the post-coital scene in The Big Lebowski when The Dude is describing his work history to Maude.

songs.title: Into the Void
songs.commentary: I would rock this double album on my Walkman so often. The packaging of it. Man I miss physical media.

songs.title: Tim, Wish You Were Born A Girl
Disconnect the Dots
songs.commentary: One of the first songs by Of Montreal I discovered. They used to be on Hoboken's own Barnone Records - so the record store had sort of passed down a love of Of Montreal for like 4-5 years before I joined. I think you can even spot one of their posters in that movie High Fidelity.

songs.title: Oslo in the Summertime
songs.commentary: Cool production and a hit song on the album that didn't become an Outback Steakhouse commercial.

songs.title: UMA
songs.commentary: There's a whole story to this song - it's actually based on a Neapolitan folk song that washer women would sing which described being courted by the king, and then being held captive by golden chains. I found the lore dump thanks to a YouTube comment. The lyrics aren't even in Japanese. The group is led by Yoshimi of the Flaming Lips' Yoshimi Battles the Pink Robots fame.

songs.title: Bat Macumba
songs.commentary: The title mashes up Batman and macumba, an Afro-Brazilian religion. The song is built like concrete poetry - the phrase 'batmacumbaiêiê batmacumbaobá' is sung in full, then a syllable drops with each repetition, changing the meaning, then builds back up. On the page, Augusto de Campos laid out the lyrics so the shape of the words forms what looks like bat wings - or Batman's ears. Even if you don't speak Portuguese, you can feel it.

songs.title: Rosa Parks
songs.commentary: Tasty track by OutKast that's subtler than some of the other hits.

songs.title: Ms. Jackson
songs.commentary: Did you know the Miss Jackson of this song is Erykah Badu's mom? Ms. Badu and Andre were dating for a while.

songs.title: Dear Boy
songs.commentary: The harmonies on this are crazy good.

songs.title: Uncle Albert / Admiral Halsey
songs.commentary: The transition about two and a half minutes into this song - that hands across the water bridge into the admiral halsey bit is so beautiful.

songs.title: Bike
songs.commentary: Yes, this is Pink Floyd, do not adjust your computer. It's superior to the stuff that followed their debut.

songs.title: The Rip
songs.commentary: Saw them live at All Tomorrow's Parties in Asbury Park and this was hypnotic. They had an animation playing with it that was beautiful.

songs.title: Wandering Star
songs.commentary: Took me a while to come around to this and appreciate it fully. Somewhere down the line these 90s albums started sounding fresh to me.

songs.title: Kiss
songs.commentary: What can I say? It's a classic.

songs.title: Crackerjack Docker
songs.commentary: A random catchy tune that's sparse that I enjoy. Seems post-punk-y to me.

songs.title: Common People
songs.commentary: There's just differences in class and if you don't get it, you don't get it. This tackles those trust fund kids dressing up as bohemians - in fact a few of them probably started bands you'll listen to next, even.

songs.title: Nosetalgia
songs.commentary: I'm kind of convinced Pusha T just loves watching HBO shows and never really did much drug dealing, but please don't tell him I said that.

songs.title: I Like to Stay Home
songs.commentary: There's so much R. Stevie Moore to listen to, and I haven't heard most of it, but I like this song a lot.

songs.title: Falling Hard
songs.commentary: I don't know how I discovered this exactly but it gave me Metric vibes in a good way.

songs.title: You Will Be Safe
songs.commentary: You will be safe.

songs.title: Exit Music (For a Film)
songs.commentary: Romeo and Juliet vibes from Radiohead - I'd sing this in the shower a lot when I was like 14, haha.

songs.title: Killing in the Name
songs.commentary: Teenage Efrain was kind of meh on RATM. Teenage Efrain was wrong.

songs.title: The Rub
songs.commentary: This is a song I wrote and recorded in 2014. I'm proudest of this one lyrically, and it's fun to get the metrics about the 4 or 5 people hearing this one each month from random locations around the world. You're part of that now, too.

songs.title: In the Snow
songs.commentary: A song that I wrote about a girlfriend who I first kissed when it started snowing for the first time that winter. It felt like a sign. I went for it, and it was great. I'm glad that was a nice memory.

songs.title: The Ocean
songs.commentary: I love a metaphor - and if Richard Hawley isn't singing about trains or motorcycles or cigarettes you better bet he's singing about water in some form. And if it's not the rain, then it's the ocean.

songs.title: For My Lover Give Some Time
songs.commentary: A beautiful song that isn't about falling in or out of love but maybe the depth of love when you've been in love for a long time.

songs.title: Free Will and Testament
songs.commentary: Reminds me of Alan Watts. I went like days without sleep in college writing my senior thesis and remember this song in some sleep deprived liminal state. So I love this song, but don't revisit it much because the sense memory is so strong.

songs.title: Saoko
songs.commentary: I was starting my first job as a designer when this came out. I was transforming, and there's empowerment in that. It would give me chills.

songs.title: Do the Strand
songs.commentary: Just the coolest collections of dudes. Brian Eno looking like Marilyn Manson in '97 and Brian Ferry's fantastic hair - so freaking cool.

songs.title: Bitter's End
songs.commentary: A great way to wrap up the record this is on. Kind of the "After Hours" of this record, in my opinion.

songs.title: Ukulele Wizard
songs.commentary: Roy Smeck was the Eddie Van Halen of the ukulele. I love how dismissive the woman in this movie is after he absolutely kills it.

songs.title: Sleepwalk
songs.commentary: A classic that's so fun to play on guitar.

songs.title: One Day
songs.commentary: New Jersey's own, I believe. This is an excellent melody.

songs.title: Strawberry Letter 23
songs.commentary: Love the melody and production here

songs.title: Oscillations
songs.commentary: Ahead of their time. Loved by John Lennon in '68 and then inspired bands like Radiohead, Stereolab and Portishead.

songs.title: Hong Kong Garden
songs.commentary: A song about Siouxsie's favorite Chinese takeout joint

songs.title: This Train
songs.commentary: She was just radiating charisma, and I love how she shushes the crowd so their clapping doesn't ruin the entire song.

songs.title: Jolly Fucker
songs.commentary: Brings to mind The Fall. Modern truth-tellers. Important people that need to share their views.

songs.title: Rill Rill
songs.commentary: This became such a popular song. It samples Funkadelic's 'Can You Get to That'

songs.title: Family Affair
songs.commentary: Can't go wrong with a classic by Sly and the Family Stone

songs.title: Just Like a Baby
songs.commentary: I love Sly's voice on this one

songs.title: Underdog
songs.commentary: Who doesn't love an underdog story. Who hasn't been there before?

songs.title: Kool Thing
songs.commentary: The iconic Sonic Youth song

songs.title: Unmade Bed
songs.commentary: The deep cut Sonic Youth song that stuck with me. I like a lot of this record.

songs.title: Baby
songs.commentary: Love how robotic and yet loose this one is. Feels kind of "Drunk Girls" by LCD Soundsystem coded.

songs.title: I Turn My Camera On
songs.commentary: This one holds up. The whole album is great, too.

songs.title: Come on My Selector
songs.commentary: Domenic was slightly older than me and going to SVA and introduced me to The Velvet Underground, Squarepusher, and Godspeed You! Black Emperor in one month. He burned me CDs and we were in an untitled post-rock band. I remember he made me watch this music video in full.

songs.title: Red Hot Car
songs.commentary: Squarepusher doesn't always have to be stark and glitchy, it can be relaxing and spacey and mellow.

songs.title: Black Coffee in Bed
songs.commentary: Is it yacht rock? I don't know - I love it.

songs.title: Cool for Cats
songs.commentary: A fun song with the word cats by Squeeze - what's not to love

songs.title: Pulling Mussels (From the Shell)
songs.commentary: Certified barbeque music

songs.title: Another Nail in My Heart
songs.commentary: Squeeze is so well produced. You can crank up the volume, it holds up.

songs.title: Tempted
songs.commentary: Patrick at the record shop got me into Squeeze

songs.title: Keep Score
songs.commentary: Saw them at Maxwell's - one of only maybe 10 people who went. They had a full lightshow setup big enough for like Terminal 5. It was awkward. This is the nephew of Wayne Coyne of The Flaming Lips.

songs.title: Smoking Pot Makes Me Not Want to Kill Myself
songs.commentary: Not the most subtle title but, not a bad song.

songs.title: Reeling in the Years
songs.commentary: I started settling into this old guy music early on in my 20s - love this song.

songs.title: Dirty Work
songs.commentary: I sing this one around the house a lot. I don't think its use in The Sopranos has helped.

songs.title: Metronomic Underground
songs.commentary: If there was an indie James Bond movie, this would be on the soundtrack.

songs.title: Higher Ground
songs.commentary: Growing up I heard the RHCP version in the Power Rangers movie I think. I like the original a lot, too.

songs.title: For Once in My Life
songs.commentary: Stevie is a songwriting master

songs.title: Super Subway Comedian
songs.commentary: This song is weird and hilarious. Reminds me of The Killing of a Chinese Bookie for some reason.

songs.title: Ghost Rider
songs.commentary: Sampled by M.I.A. on "Born Free" - this is pulsing and heavy.

songs.title: Space is the Place
songs.commentary: The first time I remember listening to local station WFMU was when I was scanning the radio and kept returning to 91.1 and hearing 'space is the place' repeat over and over. It felt surreal. I was 19. This was my first taste of Sun Ra.

songs.title: Dark Globe
songs.commentary: Dark Globe, Dark Side of the Moon... yeah I think this is Syd coping and processing after leaving Pink Floyd. Sad how he spent the rest of his life, but this song is odd and beautiful.

songs.title: Octopus
songs.commentary: Syd Barrett was the best creative part of Pink Floyd, there I said it.

songs.title: Bang a Gong (Get It On)
songs.commentary: Not just for car commercials. Woo do those backup vocals shimmer!

songs.title: Jeepster
songs.commentary: Not just for car commercials. This is my go to bar jukebox tune.

songs.title: Hello, Lucille?
songs.commentary: My two favorite parts are when he says 'She always wears pants. loooong pants.' and 'you you you'

songs.title: Born Under Punches
songs.commentary: This one holds up well, still. There's a pulsing groove to this that I love and some of my favorite songs by The Viagra Boys remind me of this song.

songs.title: Slippery People (Live)
songs.commentary: I saw The National at Forest Hills Stadium and they walked out to this song. I played it for like two months straight after that because I had kind of forgotten about it. I like this live version better than the studio version.

songs.title: Feels Like We Only Go Backwards
songs.commentary: The bass lines are so strong here.

songs.title: Yes I'm Changing
songs.commentary: Love the lyrics. They say people never change but that is bullshit.

songs.title: Look What You Made Me Do
songs.commentary: It's a guilty pleasure but I heard this song often when it came out.

songs.title: Where Have All the Rude Boys Gone
songs.commentary: My favorite Ted Leo song. I've seen him live at Maxwell's and White Eagle Hall

songs.title: Bottled in Cork
songs.commentary: New Jersey's own and with a music video cameo by Paul F. Tompkins that mocks Green Day. What's not to love?

songs.title: See No Evil
songs.commentary: I never heard the connection between Television and The Strokes, but I still like this song. This record label I interned for, Serious Business Records (this is a real thing) did some anniversary show and covered this and it was fun hearing it.

songs.title: Marline
songs.commentary: Heard about this group watching a live concert video series. I believe this is way out of print and can't find it on streaming services. It's amazing.

songs.title: Surfin' Safari
songs.commentary: I bet I'm wrong but I like to imagine this was a song that explained surfing to an audience who didn't know anything about it. Sometimes I'll break into a song about a topic and explain it, in improvised lyrics, to the tune of Surfin' Safari. It's ... it's quirky.

songs.title: Step on Me
songs.commentary: Can you find a better song about being exhausted in a relationship? I can't.

songs.title: Lovefool
songs.commentary: Criminally underrated group. Of course this is a catchy amazing number, but seriously - lots more good stuff on this album!

songs.title: Human Fly
songs.commentary: Dirty and gonzo-spooky

songs.title: Fire in Cairo
songs.commentary: Did you know early The Cure sounded like this? So cool, I didn't when I was turned on to their first album.

songs.title: Primary
songs.commentary: A favorite of mine by The Cure

songs.title: Eat Y'self Fitter
songs.commentary: My favorite song by The Fall. Maybe more relevant in the age of AI, maybe super ironic you're hearing it through this uh vehicle of sorts? EAT EACH OTHER!

songs.title: Totally Wired
songs.commentary: Drink a couple cups of coffee and get totally wired

songs.title: Thank You Jack White (For the Fiber-Optic Jesus That You Gave Me)
songs.commentary: This is the closest you'll get to anything with Jack White in my music, haha. It's a quirky Flaming Lips b-side that makes me happy.

songs.title: Virgo Self-Esteem Broadcast
songs.commentary: Abstract music by The Flaming Lips. Listen to the full record if you like this. This song leads into a driving catchy tune. There's other songs off Embryonic I love, too.

songs.title: See the Leaves
songs.commentary: Mother nature. She persists and survives and transforms. See the leaves - they're dying again. See the sun, it's dying again. I love songs about cycles. Songs themselves are cycles.

songs.title: I'm Evil, Jack
songs.commentary: My friend Jack had a health emergency and survived, thank God. A concert was organized for him at Maxwell's after he recovered a bit and I had the pleasure of being a part of a concert where local musicians selected from a list of "Jack" themed songs he picked. No one wanted this one, haha. It's filthy. I had to sing about killing and I think Jack's grandmother was there? I didn't hold back a bit. I could hear Jack laughing and that kept me going. This song always makes me smile now.

songs.title: Three Changes
songs.artist: The Good, the Bad & the Queen
songs.commentary: A super group with Damon Albarn - sick.

songs.title: Main Offender
songs.commentary: Missed out on seeing The Hives live at Maxwell's. A major live show regret.

songs.title: Hate to Say I Told You So
songs.commentary: It was a huge hit and lots of fun, I still play this one from time to time.

songs.title: No Wow
songs.commentary: The Kills, especially their first two albums, feel very at home with The Stooges and The Velvet Underground, to me.

songs.title: Fried My Little Brains
songs.commentary: During The Kills concert I saw - I locked eyes with "Hotel" the guitarist. He had a bandana around his neck and was strumming his hollow body. I wanted to be just like him for a while, haha.

songs.title: Cat Claw
songs.commentary: Just before I saw The Kills at Maxwell's I thought, who is that drunk woman and is she dangerous - then I realized she was the lead singer of the band. It was a great show.

songs.title: Wait
songs.commentary: The first band I saw at Maxwell's.

songs.title: Victoria
songs.commentary: Fun and singable. I never expect this as an option for karaoke but if it were available I would take it every time.

songs.title: This Time Tomorrow
songs.commentary: My favorite song by The Kinks with Victoria really really close behind. I learned of it from the Darjeeling Limited soundtrack but to this day I've not seen that movie. Don't really care much for Owen Wilson.

songs.title: Pass This On
songs.commentary: I liked this song, then saw the video, and then liked the whole thing even more.

songs.title: Heartbeats
songs.commentary: This was covered by Jose Gonzalez. Anyway - I prefer the original, and remember the buzz when they did CMJ

songs.title: A Pretty Girl Is Like
songs.commentary: Schmaltzy and corny but cute. Part of 69 Love Songs, an album that has... well, you can probably guess.

songs.title: All My Little Words
songs.commentary: Fun Fact: I worked security for The Magnetic Fields in the Lowes Theater in Jersey City, NJ. They didn't really need security. They were nice, but complained about the crudités plate.

songs.title: Take the Veil Cerpin Taxt
songs.commentary: I learned about The Mars Volta while working at a coffee shop when I was 16. Later I recorded music with a producer who was in the same circles as these guys in El Paso. Small world. Rick Rubin produced this abstract concept album about a poet friend who died after coming out of a coma. This song closes the record - it's devastating and beautiful.

songs.title: Till Then
songs.commentary: The chord progressions are classic and the bridge turn - it's just so nostalgic. I like to pair it with Sons of the Pioneers if it's on a playlist - they work pretty well together.

songs.title: We Fly High (Where Eagles Dare)
songs.commentary: My boss at Tunes, the record store I worked at, hadn't heard of The Misfits or forgot. One time I was playing it and he came out and was vibing to it.

songs.title: Skull
songs.commentary: Lodi, NJ's own The Misfits! Not to be confused with the obese cover band that plays covers with reworked food-related lyrics, The Misfats (this is a real thing, look it up.)

songs.title: I'm Straight
songs.commentary: I think the singing style Jonathan Richman uses here contributed a lot to James Murphy's approach. This is a pretty badass straight edge anthem.

songs.title: Pablo Picasso
songs.commentary: I do actually think that Pablo Picasso was called an asshole. In fact, I think Wilfredo Lam is (gasp!) better.

songs.title: Steak for Chicken
songs.commentary: It's clever how there are two sets of lyrics at the same time. So whatever you decide to hear - that's on you. Then, kind of like "The Murder Mystery" by The Velvet Underground, elements from either set of lyrics will kind of spill over into one another.

songs.title: Majesty
songs.commentary: My favorite Music Tapes song - it reminds me of snowy weather

songs.title: The Minister of Longitude
songs.commentary: I saw these guys live at Maxwell's and Julian was so nice but they smelled really bad

songs.title: S.F. Sorrow Is Born
songs.commentary: No one was allowed to make bad music in 1967 or 1968.

songs.title: Baron Saturday
songs.commentary: What cool production, huh?

songs.title: Talkin' About the Good Times
songs.commentary: This is a psychedelic classic.

songs.title: Walking Through My Dreams
songs.commentary: Beautiful, absolutely beautiful and recorded at Abbey Road.

songs.title: Who Are Parents?
songs.commentary: Wikipedia says - "The Shaggs formed at the insistence of their father, Austin Wiggin, who believed that his mother had predicted their rise to fame." The tempo's instability is actually nauseating if you pay attention too long. It's fascinating outsider music.

songs.title: I Know It's Over
songs.commentary: So dramatic, haha. Great lyrics

songs.title: Heaven Knows I'm Miserable Now
songs.commentary: Some songs you need to be older to understand and you can file this one under that. I was looking for a job and then I found a job! Haha

songs.title: Strychnine
songs.commentary: I don't think I would like the taste. I love the delivery and vibes. I believe these guys.

songs.title: Ball of the Dead Rat
songs.commentary: This group opened for The Spinto Band at Maxwell's and then broke up. They really outshined The Spinto Band and I wish I could get in touch with the dude who wrote this song. It's so good and his vocal tone is the best.

songs.title: Sweet Jane
songs.commentary: My favorite Velvets song, the lyrics are brilliant.

songs.title: Candy Says
songs.commentary: What do you think I'd be if I could get away from me? A question worth asking.

songs.title: The Murder Mystery
songs.commentary: Pick a side of your headphones and follow it. There are many threads. I like how themes from one set of lyrics or the story bleed into each other.

songs.title: Friends of Mine
songs.commentary: A feel good song honoring the couples in your life and being happy for them.

songs.title: Time of the Season
songs.commentary: As a kid I remembered this from a Sprite commercial, but it's much better than that.

songs.title: Numerology
songs.commentary: Esoteric rock? I dunno. I like the mystique.

songs.title: Still In Love With You (Live)
songs.commentary: Very rarely do I enjoy the live version of a song more than the original recording, but this is an experience, man.

songs.title: What's He Building?
songs.commentary: We've all been there. For me it's the upstairs neighbor. They seem to move the furniture a lot.

songs.title: Don't Go Into That Barn
songs.commentary: Late stage Waits gets really loud and awesome - I love the wailing.

songs.title: How's It Gonna End
songs.commentary: Doom poet

songs.title: God's Away on Business
songs.commentary: There was a viral video of Cookie Monster made to look like he was singing this. Now you'll not be able to unhear it either.

songs.title: Tô
songs.commentary: The lyrics are brilliant but you need to know some Portuguese. Go look for an English translation, the lyrics work in dualities. It's beautiful, it's ugly. Roughly 'I'm explaining you to confuse you / I'm confusing you to enlighten you / I'm enlightening you so I can blind you / I'm blinding you so I can guide you'

songs.title: Waiting Around to Die
songs.commentary: What a bleak, sad, song. I liked covering this one a lot, but I don't know how it was usually received.

songs.title: Meshkalina
songs.commentary: I found this one on WFMU, it's a local radio station that plays all kinds of music. Highly recommend them for more cool music.

songs.title: Wolf Like Me
songs.commentary: Peak 2006/7 - this was also in a lot of TV and Movies too I feel like.

songs.title: Sugar on my Tongue
songs.commentary: Such a fun hit that deserves all the plays it gets

songs.title: Pop the Glock
songs.commentary: Uffie was the original Ke$ha.

songs.title: The American Metaphysical Circus
songs.commentary: Kudos if you can tough it out through this one, it's a masterpiece but it's challenging. Step up to the challenge!

songs.title: How Can You Luv Me
songs.commentary: The first Unknown Mortal Orchestra song I really connected with.

songs.title: Diamond Day
songs.commentary: Discovered this during the freak folk revival in the early 2000s - what a beautiful voice

songs.title: After Hours
songs.commentary: Maureen Tucker, the drummer, is so sweet in this song. It closes the album and it's awesome.

songs.title: My Echo, My Shadow and Me
songs.commentary: This was such a sadsack song to crawl into during my quarter-life crisis. Warm and classic.

songs.title: We'll Meet Again
songs.commentary: I know this song from Dr. Strangelove. I think it was set to play on radio automatically if nuclear bombs were to destroy a lot of the country? Not sure about that, but I do know they play this at the end of My Morning Jacket concerts, so it always makes me think of those shows, too.

songs.title: Perlas de Pensamientos
songs.commentary: Dark bolero vibes. You are an international agent and take a slow sip from a stiff drink while you watch the palm trees sway in the breeze under the moonlight.

songs.title: Yes I'm Lonely
songs.commentary: Yes, the director of Buffalo '66 made a record and while a lot of it is forgettable, I do love this track from it.

songs.title: Blister in the Sun
songs.commentary: This song was released in 1983 and still feels modern.

songs.title: Nippon Budokan
songs.commentary: Played a show in Secaucus with this group. To me they were like the local version of The Black Lips and I think they even covered "Boomerang" by them.

songs.title: Alone Again, Naturally
songs.commentary: Some of the saddest lyrics and a fantastic melody. Unfortunately even the Nina Simone cover of this one isn't sung sad enough. This version comes close though.

songs.title: Ice Castles
songs.commentary: This is a Ween song that does not sound like a Ween song. It sounds like how it might sound if you were put under a spell captured on video on VHS

songs.title: Gabrielle
songs.commentary: Ween doing a good job of channeling Thin Lizzy here in my opinion. This rocks. If I was named Gabrielle this would be my entrance music to every meeting or event.

songs.title: Bananas and Blow
songs.commentary: Ween taking a trip to Mock-aritaville

songs.title: El Scorcho
songs.commentary: Self effacing Rivers Cuomo is enjoyable

songs.title: Say it Ain't So
songs.commentary: Teenage Efrain liked this song a lot

songs.title: Impossible Germany
songs.commentary: What a guitar solo by Nels Cline on this one. I have no problem with Nels Cline era Wilco and love this record. Maybe more than even Yankee Hotel Foxtrot (gasp!)

songs.title: Jesus, Etc.
songs.commentary: Beautiful song that has made me cry, I dunno why? Makes me think of 9/11. It was written and recorded just before it actually... I dunno. Sometimes you get messages?

songs.title: Better Change Your Mind
songs.commentary: This was one of those key world music go-tos of my collection as I expanded my horizons. I love the lo-fi of it.

songs.title: The Glow
songs.commentary: The Last Dragon is a fun 80s movie with deceivingly complex cultural games its playing. At the end of the day, it is a Motown production and the music is great even if it's tied to its times. Who is the master, Leroy?

songs.title: Seer
songs.commentary: I love this retro-Black Sabbath vibe and the guitar tones are fantastic.

songs.title: Rip Van Winkle
songs.commentary: J. Mascis from Dinosaur Jr's other project. I like this one better, to be honest.

songs.title: C.R.E.A.M.
songs.commentary: A classic, right?

songs.title: The Day the World Turned Day Glo
songs.commentary: Classic proto-riot grrrl

songs.title: Rumpus Room
songs.commentary: Explodes into an infectious groove. It's druggy and feels sweaty somehow. I didn't know songs could feel sweaty and stinky. COVID boredom. Unwrap a cuuuutttiiieee

songs.title: You Can Have It All
songs.commentary: Beautiful and simple and full of heart. Why isn't this more well known?

songs.title: Center of Gravity
songs.commentary: Hoboken-based samba? Spanish band name inspired by a player on The Mets? Hanukkah extravaganzas every year? I love Yo La Tengo

songs.title: My Dog Was Lost But Now He's Found
This Town Ain't Big Enough For Both of Us
Beautiful People
songs.commentary: Teenage Efrain was a big Marilyn Manson fan. The employees at Sam Goody would reluctantly sell me his CDs but warned me, "This is going to get you in trouble, kid."

songs.title: Get Over It
songs.commentary: This was the first OK GO song I found, I loved the music video actually. Little did I know how I'd be sort of intertwined with them.

songs.title: Paper Heart
songs.commentary: Pure sugary pop. This would play alongside Nine Inch Nails and Marilyn Manson and Phish during one of my weirder phases in high school.

songs.title: Swing Swing
songs.commentary: Teenage Efrain was playing this on his Walkman after downloading the album from Napster - which would take 8 hours. If you didn't grow up then, you should stop and really think about that. The speed at which we get things now is astounding.

songs.title: California
songs.commentary: Philly's own - singing about the west coast.

songs.title: 1000 Miles Per Hour
songs.commentary: I would cover this song at the coffee shop when I was first performing live, too. A bit sentimental but, sweet.

songs.title: Delicate
songs.commentary: I used to cover this song when I would first play music live at a local coffee shop. It taught me about dynamics since the song starts low and relaxes before a booming crescendo. It was one of the first moments I felt confident in my singing and it was a crowd pleaser I could reliably bust out.

songs.title: Volcano
songs.commentary: What a lovely duet. It's mainstream, it's...maybe sneaking into Easy Listening but, it's nice. I love her voice.

songs.title: So Good at Being in Trouble
Goodthing
songs.commentary: At a certain point exploring downtempo House I realized I could get a lot of the similar feelings that I'd get from classic psych rock. The vocal sample on this one is fun.

songs.title: SP12 Beat
songs.commentary: This scratches a lot of itches for me. It sounds lo-fi adjacent like bedroom made, has this world music feel with the instruments and the steady pulse of hypnotic electronic I like — steady with subtle variations and morphing like post-rock or krautrock.

songs.title: Hellrap
songs.commentary: First found this as a bed of music for a Rick Owens show and it probably spoke a little to Teenage Efrain. But after I looked up the lyrics it's a pretty sweet song wrapped up in spookiness. He's touring the world and leaning into being a "genre-hopper...vicious like Sid" and admitting "Fans think I'm the man but really I'm just a sad band member with bands." and complaining how he hasn't seen his mother since February. That's what makes him want to "kill somethin'." He misses his mother. Who among us? Am I right?

songs.title: Escapism
songs.commentary: Beyond this just being a banger, I'm tangentially connected to both these artists. Raye was produced by the brother of one of my previous co-workers, and 070 Shake is from my hometown and represents the zipcode in the first three digits of her name (also had a collective of artists from nearby towns using it as a tag since all the local zips began with 070). Respect on her for breaking out and doing cool shit and calling out our local high school as not really supporting her much at all — yep that tracks.

songs.title: Gnossienne No. 1
songs.commentary: A go-to for wandering late at night and thinking about it all.

songs.title: rain bird interlude
songs.commentary: An unexpected find thanks to the algorithm, if I'm being honest. I love how delicate it is and it works well with Bruno Major or Joji on a playlist.

songs.title: Mirage
songs.commentary: Orion Sun is New Jersey's Own, Tiffany Majette. This one feels at home with so much in my collection. I just wish it was longer. Its guitar lines remind me of Cartola.

songs.title: Bombay
songs.commentary: If Animal Collective was Colombian. This dude also produced a lot of cool music from artists including Rosalía.

songs.title: White Gloves
songs.commentary: Seventh chords, heavenly, with a nice snare tone and restrained guitar licks.

songs.title: Oncle Jazz
songs.commentary: What a fun way to open a record. If you like the vibes, go listen to this entire record. efrain.fm will still be here when you're done.

songs.title: Show Me How
songs.commentary: My favorite Men I Trust song. I need to see them live someday. The choice to have that lead guitar with a touch of tremolo follow the main melody line... that was the right choice.

songs.title: telepatía
songs.commentary: When I can enjoy modern music in Spanish because I'm bi-lingual, it feels like a special power. For the non-speakers, it's a song about longing, and wishing one could make love telepathically. Sensual.

songs.title: Moonlight
songs.commentary: This was my second encounter with Kali Uchis. I liked her collab with Tyler, The Creator, but this song was so good. The Spanish line is great — "I see a doll when I look in the mirror — kiss kiss." Catchy and sultry.

songs.title: I Want To Marry An Egghead
I Was Dancing in the Lesbian Bar
Reflective Surfaces
songs.commentary: Rachel's was a band I discovered when I was hanging out with Domenic who was into post-rock and also shared Godspeed You! Black Emperor with me. We were in an untitled post-rock band for a while, it was fun.

songs.title: Jailbreak
songs.commentary: If I see a jukebox - this is always a front runner.

songs.title: The Boys Are Back In Town
songs.commentary: Certified barbecue music.

songs.title: Anthems For A Seventeen Year-Old Girl
songs.commentary: This song makes me think of Scott Pilgrim vs. The World. It does a good job of capturing teenage angst.

songs.title: Svefn-g-englar
songs.commentary: I was doing floating sessions for a while — you know, sensory deprivation tanks? Anyway, it was hard to just return to the world after an hour of floating without triggering your senses. So, this was what would play on repeat as I sat for a bit in the lobby drinking tea and then driving home. I was always the best, most forgiving driver on those trips home.

songs.title: Burndt Jamb
songs.commentary: Maladroit was not loved by all Weezer fans and I can't say I return to the album in full often, but I love this one and wish it was longer.

songs.title: Like a Ship
songs.artist: Pastor T.L. Barrett and the Youth for Christ Choir

songs.title: Pull Up
songs.commentary: Saw this group open for Jungle in Brooklyn. Their set was great but this song in particular stuck with me.

songs.title: Saving All My Love For You
Vinegar Hill
songs.commentary: I love this piece and wish it were longer. It's so delicate and feels like that short space between dusk and dawn. The melody swirls and dances and builds up and builds up until it all tumbles in a shimmering and satisfying fall.

songs.title: I'm Sad the Goat Just Died Today
Folsom Prison Blues
songs.commentary: I think this song is very punk rock. Such good storytelling and the part I always loved was, "When I was just a baby my mama told me 'Son, always be a good boy, don't ever play with guns.' But I shot a man in Reno just to watch him die."

songs.title: Cocaine (Live at Folsom Prison)
songs.commentary: This song hits different live in prison. The ambiance of this live album with the occasional administrative messages is perfect.

songs.title: The First Time Ever I Saw Your Face
Move On Up
songs.commentary: I always loved this classic, but now I think about it every New Years. Why? Because I rang in 2009 with My Morning Jacket. To open the show they fixed drinks at a bar on stage while "What Are You Doing New Year's Eve?" played in the background before exploding into a cover of this one. It set the tone for the night and was one of the best concerts I ever attended.

songs.title: Pusherman
songs.commentary: Do we cheer or villainize the Pusherman? It's from the Blaxploitation classic Super Fly, but it's one of the best soundtracks period, like overall.

songs.title: (Sittin' On) The Dock of the Bay
That's How Strong My Love Is
Lifetime Monologue
songs.commentary: Spoken word by Lou Rawls here. Every day they work.

songs.title: The Revolution Will Not Be Televised
songs.commentary: I love its commentary on TV as a distraction during the civil rights movement. There's a lot to unpack about that relationship between what was broadcast television and Black America at this time.

songs.title: Whitey on the Moon
songs.commentary: Here Gil Juxtaposes the expenses of the space race and America's ability to do the impossible and put a man on the moon while he struggles with basic living conditions and rising prices. Where's he going to send those bills? You'll see.

songs.title: Enough
songs.commentary: This one in my opinion is more scathing and brutal than "The Revolution Will Not Be Televised" and by a lot! He realizes the horrors of slavery and grapples with his anger knowing his ancestors were mistreated and recognizing the way that has shaped his experience growing up. The final lines are so sharp.

songs.title: On Coming from a Broken Home Pt. 1
songs.commentary: Gil telling his own story. There's a notable sample here — Kanye's Flashing Lights. It was Gil's response to West sampling him without credit. He decided to do the same.

songs.title: On Coming from a Broken Home Pt. 2
songs.commentary: Gil telling his own story. There's a notable sample here — Kanye's Flashing Lights. It was Gil's response to West sampling him without credit. He decided to do the same.

songs.title: I've Gotta Get A Message To You
Every Lion Hearted Christian Man Will Show You
The Rip
songs.commentary: Saw them live at All Tomorrow's Parties in Asbury Park and this was hypnotic. They had an animation playing with it that was beautiful.

songs.title: Bunny Ain't No Kind of Rider
When the Last Time
songs.commentary: Add it to your gym playlist rotation and watch your personal records break, baby. Pharrell produced banger.

songs.title: Keys Open Doors
songs.commentary: Hell Hath No Fury was my introduction to Clipse and this one in particular I liked. The choir-like pads, the repeating rough loop, it's great.

songs.title: I Want a House
songs.commentary: One of my favorite discoveries. It's deep without needing to be loud. It's yearning... it's beautiful.

songs.title: Mess Your Hair Up
songs.commentary: Their older stuff had such a cool psych bend. The new stuff? No comment. The shift like a minute and a half in is a trip!

songs.title: Feral Verdure
songs.commentary: Got to see them open for A Silver Mt. Zion and became an instant fan after this song. It builds and builds to an amazing final minute of pure vulnerability that you need to stick around for.
